    <exercise xml:id="exer_sec51-3">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use mathematical induction to prove each of the following:
        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task xml:id="exer_inductionsum-a">
            <statement>
            <p>
              For each natural number <m>n</m>,
              <m>2 + 5 + 8 + \cdots + \left( {3n - 1} \right) = \dfrac{{n\left( {3n + 1} 
              \right)}}{2}</m>.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                For each  <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, let  <m>P( n )</m> be,
                <m>2 + 5 + 8 +  \cdots  + (3n - 1) = \dfrac{{n( {3n + 1} )}}{2}</m>. 
                When we use <m>n = 1</m>, the summation on the left side of the equation is 2, 
                and the right side is <m>\dfrac{1(3 \cdot 1 + 1)}{2} = 2</m>.  Therefore, 
                <m>P( 1 )</m>  is true.   For the inductive step, let <m>k \in \mathbb{N}</m> 
                and assume that
                <m>P \left( k \right)</m> is true.  Then,
                <me>
                  2 + 5 + 8 + \cdots  + \left( {3k - 1} \right) = \frac{{k \left( {3k + 1} \right)}}{2}
                </me>.
                We now add <m>3 \left( k + 1 \right) - 1</m> to both sides of this equation. 
                This gives
                <md>
                  <mrow>2 + 5 + 8 + \cdots  + (3k - 1) \amp</mrow>
                  <mrow>+ 3 \left( {k + 1} \right)-1 \amp =
                  \frac{{k \left( {3k + 1} \right)}}{2} + \left( 3 \left( k + 1 \right) - 1 \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{{k \left( {3k + 1} \right)}}{2} + \left( {3k + 2} \right)</mrow>
                </md>
                If we now combine the terms on the right side of the equation into a single 
                fraction, we obtain
                <md>
                  <mrow>2 + 5 +  \cdots  + \left( {3k - 1} \right) + 3 \left( {k + 1} \right)-1 
                  \amp = \frac{k \left( 3k + 1 \right) + 6k+4}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{ 3k^2 + 7k + 4}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{ \left( k + 1 \right) \left( 3k + 4 \right)}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{ \left( k + 1 \right) \left( 3 \left( k + 1 \right) + 1 \right)}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                This proves that if  <m>P\left( k \right)</m> is true, then 
                <m>P\left( {k + 1} \right)</m> is true.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
