    <exercise xml:id="exer_wallis">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In calculus, it can be shown that
          <md>
            <mrow>\int_{}^{} \sin^{\,2} x \, dx \amp = 
            \frac{x}{2} - \frac{1}{2} \sin x \cos x + c  \text{ and }</mrow>
            
            <mrow>\int_{}{} \cos^{\,2} x \, dx \amp = 
            \frac{x}{2} + \frac{1}{2} \sin x \cos x + c</mrow>
          </md>.
          Using integration by parts,
          it is also possible to prove that for each natural number <m>n</m>,
          <md>
            <mrow>\int_{}{} \sin^{\,n} x \, dx \amp = -\frac{1}{n} \sin^{n-1}x \cos x + 
            \frac{n-1}{n} \int{}{} \sin^{\,n-2}x \, dx  \text{ and }</mrow>
            
            <mrow>\int_{}{} \cos^{\,n} x \, dx \amp = \frac{1}{n} \cos^{n-1}x \sin x + 
            \frac{n-1}{n} \int{}{} \cos^{\,n-2}x \, dx</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task>
            <p>
              Determine the values of
                <me>
                  \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin^{\,2} x \, dx \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad 
                  \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin^{\,4} x \, dx
                </me>.
            </p>
          </task>
          <task>
            <p>
              Use mathematical induction to prove that for each natural number <m>n</m>,
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin^{\,2n}x \, dx \amp = 
                  \frac{1 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \cdots (2n - 1)}{2 \cdot 4 \cdot 6 \cdots (2n)} 
                  \frac{\pi}{2}  \text{ and }</mrow>
                  <mrow>\int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin^{\,2n+1}x \, dx \amp = 
                  \frac{2 \cdot 4 \cdot 6 \cdots (2n)}{1 \cdot 3  \cdot 5 \cdots (2n + 1)}</mrow>
                </md>.
                These are known as the <term>Wallis sine formulas</term>.
                <idx><h>Wallis sine formulas</h></idx>
            </p>
          </task>
          <task>
            <p>
              Use mathematical induction to prove that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{0}^{\pi/2} \cos^{\,2n}x \, dx \amp = 
                  \frac{1 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \cdots (2n - 1)}{2 \cdot 4 \cdot 6 \cdots (2n)} 
                  \frac{\pi}{2}  \text{ and }</mrow>
